00:25:58,049 --> 00:25:58,229
Yes.

611
00:25:58,690 --> 00:25:58,910
Yes.

612
00:25:59,850 --> 00:26:02,032
What's the point of even having a booth

613
00:26:02,272 --> 00:26:06,234
if the whole point is making connections or relationships

614
00:26:06,334 --> 00:26:06,795
with others?

615
00:26:07,560 --> 00:26:10,261
So having a booth, first of all, is a great way

616
00:26:10,721 --> 00:26:11,722
getting into an event.

617
00:26:12,082 --> 00:26:15,643
But on top of connections, it gets you

618
00:26:15,823 --> 00:26:20,205
exposure that translates into sales over time.

619
00:26:20,305 --> 00:26:22,086
For example, North of the Line ended up

620
00:26:22,106 --> 00:26:24,547
making a video about Move or Die because he

621
00:26:24,587 --> 00:26:25,888
got to play it at an event.

622
00:26:26,068 --> 00:26:27,789
And it's a different thing when you can go up to a booth

623
00:26:27,829 --> 00:26:29,009
and play the game or play a game.

624
00:26:29,309 --> 00:26:32,912
have me show it on a phone, which is not the same thing.

625
00:26:34,213 --> 00:26:36,134
And another cool thing that I observed

626
00:26:36,214 --> 00:26:38,175
when going to events, for example,

627
00:26:38,195 --> 00:26:40,837
I went to Gamescom several years in a row,

628
00:26:41,017 --> 00:26:44,220
and the first year, people never heard of the game.

629
00:26:44,620 --> 00:26:46,221
But then the second year, when I was stepping away

630
00:26:46,261 --> 00:26:48,423
from the booth and blending in into the crowd,

631
00:26:48,443 --> 00:26:50,504
I was hearing people walk by and go like,

632
00:26:50,724 --> 00:26:52,365
oh, I remember that game, that's Move or Die,

633
00:26:52,405 --> 00:26:53,226
we played it last year.

634
00:26:53,746 --> 00:26:57,109
So it gradually builds exposure, so I think it's,

635
00:26:57,709 --> 00:26:59,730
pretty worth it on top of the connections you make.

636
00:27:02,332 --> 00:27:02,552
Yeah.

637
00:27:03,673 --> 00:27:03,733
Hi.

638
00:27:03,813 --> 00:27:05,494
So you mentioned when you have a lot of spectators

639
00:27:05,534 --> 00:27:07,935
or players at your booth, that breeds more.

640
00:27:08,455 --> 00:27:10,937
But it's also my experience that if you have none,

641
00:27:10,957 --> 00:27:13,118
that keeps more away.

642
00:27:13,138 --> 00:27:13,718
Right.

643
00:27:13,758 --> 00:27:15,579
Any tips for getting out of that?

644
00:27:16,892 --> 00:27:21,876
So that's kind of tricky because spectators always have,

645
00:27:21,916 --> 00:27:24,137
so just people walking around always have this thing

646
00:27:24,177 --> 00:27:26,859
where you try to get them to play the game

647
00:27:26,960 --> 00:27:28,641
and they always go like, nah, I'm just watching.

648
00:27:30,402 --> 00:27:32,724
And I mean, the reason why they're there is to play games.

649
00:27:32,904 --> 00:27:34,806
So you have to figure out a way to get them

650
00:27:35,286 --> 00:27:36,827
to actually try out your game.

651
00:27:37,768 --> 00:27:39,329
And a very effective way of doing this,

652
00:27:39,469 --> 00:27:42,131
I figured out that is to just hand them the controller

653
00:27:42,211 --> 00:27:43,512
and go like, hey, hold this for a second.

654
00:27:43,673 --> 00:27:44,813
And they just walk away.

655
00:27:45,674 --> 00:27:47,055
And I actually did that, and it works.

656
00:27:47,395 --> 00:27:48,096
It's amazing.

657
00:27:48,156 --> 00:27:50,277
Because then they're like, well, might as well try it now.

658
00:27:52,419 --> 00:27:56,041
So yeah, I guess you have to get creative with how you make

659
00:27:56,061 --> 00:27:58,323
your game seem not intimidating.

660
00:27:58,343 --> 00:27:59,744
Thanks.

661
00:28:00,304 --> 00:28:00,564
Thank you.

